A N A C T
RELATING TO EDUCATION -- CERTIFICATION OF TEACHERS
Introduced By: Representative William W. O'Brien
Date Introduced: February 26, 2025
Referred To: House Education
It is enacted by the General Assembly as follows:
1 SECTION 1. Section 16-11-1 of the General Laws in Chapter 16-11 entitled "Certification
2 of Teachers [See Title 16 Chapter 97 — The Rhode Island Board of Education Act]" is hereby
3 amended to read as follows:
4 16-11-1. Certification of public school teachers required — Deductions from state aid
5 for noncompliance.
6 No person shall be employed to teach, as principal or assistant, in any school supported
7 wholly or in part by public money unless the person shall have a certificate of qualification issued
8 by or under the authority of the board of regents for elementary and secondary education. Provided,
9 however, that any person who is employed as a part time speech and language pathologist at the
10 Rhode Island School for the Deaf, for a period of not less than ten (10) years prior to July 11, 1990,
11 shall not be required to have a certificate of qualification, and shall be exempt from the provisions
12 of this section which require the certificate. Provided, further, however, that any person who is
13 employed as a physical education teacher shall not by required to have a certification in adaptive
14 physical education, unless they were hired after July 1, 2025. In case any city or town shall pay or
15 cause to be paid any of the public money to any person for teaching who did not, at the time of
16 teaching, hold a certificate, then the department of elementary and secondary education shall deduct
17 a sum equal to the amount so paid from the amount of the state’s money due, or which may
18 thereafter become due, to the city or town, before giving his or her order in favor of the city or town
19 for any of the public money under the provisions of §§ 16-1-10, 16-1-11, and 16-5-22.

1 SECTION 2. This act shall take effect upon passage.
